-----------------------GREP---GLOBAL REGULAR EXPRESSION PRINT--"COMMAND-LINE TOOL USED TO SEARCH FOR A STRING OF CHARACTERS IN A SPECIFIED FILE."-----------------------------
grep <options> <pattern> <filename>

1)grep -c unix grep.txt ---> count the number of lines where pattern match

2)grep -h unix grep.txt---> display the matched lines

3) grep -i unix grep.txt--->ignores the case of matching

4) grep -n unix grep.txt---> display the number and lines of mathced pattern

5)grep -v unix grep.txt-->prints out all the lines that do not matches the pattern #invert lines

6) grep -e unix grep.txt---> taking the pattern until full-stop.

7) grep -f grep.txt unix grep.txt--->takes pattern from file once per line

8)grep -o unix grep.txt--->print only the matched parts of a matching line,
 with each such part on a separate output line.

9)grep -w easy grep.txt--->match the whole word

10)grep -ir multiuser /home/hpcsa51/documents--->search the pattern in the directory

11)grep "^unix" grep.txt---> starting with the lines having pattern

12)grep "unix$" grep.txt---> ending with the lines having pattern

13)grep -R [Search] [directory]-->prints the searched pattern in the given directory recursively in all the files.

